<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900511-0003</DOCNO><DOCID>900511-0003.</DOCID><HL>   CAE Profit Plunged   94% in Fiscal Year;   U.S. Results Cited</HL><DATE>05/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   T.CAE</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   TORONTO -- CAE Industries Ltd. said lower earnings fromthe company's U.S. operations and accounting changes resultedin a 94% drop in net income for the year ended March 31.   CAE, a dominant player in the military and commercialsimulation markets, reported net income of 2.7 millionCanadian dollars (US$2.3 million) or three cents (Cdn) ashare, in the 1990 fiscal year, down from C$42.8 million, or55 cents (Cdn) a share, the previous year. Revenue rose 33%to C$1.12 billion from C$838.8 million.</LP><TEXT>   CAE attributed the decline to changes in accountingpractices, which increased the company's income taxes and theamount of a write-down on two unprofitable contracts at itsU.S. operations, CAELink. Income taxes payable in fiscal 1990rose to C$19.1 million from C$11.7 million in 1989. Thewrite-down, originally estimated at C$10.5 million, nowamounts to C$17.5 million.   Interest expenses also rose by C$15 million to C$42.9million.   CAE said that without the accounting changes, the companywould have reported net of about 30 cents (Cdn) a share.   CAE acquired Singer Co.'s Link Flight Simulation Divisionin 1988 for $550 million. The company has embarked on arestructuring program which CAE's senior vice president offinance, John Caldwell, said will improve the unit'sprofitability in a few years' time.   David Race, the company's president and chief executiveofficer, said he expects to see &quot;modest growth&quot; in revenueand profitability in its fiscal 1991 year. He declined togive a specific estimate.   &quot;Based on the . . . progress we expect to make this year,I am optimistic that fiscal 1992 should show a return toimproved growth in revenue and earnings,&quot; Mr. Race said.</TEXT></DOC>